Duck typing is a programming concept that is not specific to any particular language, but is often associated with dynamic languages such as Python, Ruby, and JavaScript. Duck typing is a style of typing in which an object's methods and properties determine the valid semantics, rather than its inheritance from a particular class or implementation of a specific interface. The name of the concept refers to the duck test, attributed to James Whitcomb Riley, which may be phrased as follows:

> When I see a bird that walks like a duck and swims like a duck and quacks like a duck, I call that bird a duck.

In other words, if it looks like a duck and acts like a duck, it's a duck. In programming terms, if an object has the right methods and properties, it can be used as if it were an instance of the expected type or class, regardless of its actual type or class.

In TypeScript, duck typing is used to determine if an object can be used in a certain context based on its structure rather than its explicit type. This is often used in conjunction with structural subtyping, which allows a type to be considered a subtype of another type as long as it has all the required properties and methods. This makes TypeScript a more flexible and expressive language than strictly typed languages like Java or C++.

Here's an example of duck typing in TypeScript:
```typescript
interface Duck {
  quack(): void;
  swim(): void;
}

class MallardDuck implements Duck {
  quack() {
    console.log("Quack, quack!");
  }

  swim() {
    console.log("Swimming...");
  }
}

class Dog {
  bark() {
    console.log("Woof, woof!");
  }

  swim() {
    console.log("Swimming...");
  }
}

function makeDuckNoise(duck: Duck) {
  duck.quack();
}

const mallard = new MallardDuck();
const fido = new Dog();

makeDuckNoise(mallard); // This works fine
makeDuckNoise(fido); // This will cause a TypeScript error
```
In this example, the `MallardDuck` class implements the `Duck` interface, so it can be used anywhere a `Duck` is expected. However, the `Dog` class does not implement the `Duck` interface, even though it has a `swim` method. Therefore, it cannot be used in the `makeDuckNoise` function, which expects a `Duck` argument. The TypeScript compiler will catch this error at compile time rather than at runtime, making the code more reliable and easier to maintain.

To create a Discord bot with a ban command using Discord.js v14, you'll first need to install Node.js and npm (Node Package Manager) on your machine. After that, create a new folder for your bot and initialize a new Node.js project by running `npm init -y`.

Next, install the required dependencies: discord.js and @discordjs/rest by running:

```
npm install discord.js@14 @discordjs/rest@1
```

Now, create a new file named `bot.js` inside your project folder and paste the following code:

```javascript
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits, Partials, Collection } = require('discord.js');
const { REST } = require('@discordjs/rest');
const { Routes } = require('discord-api-types/v9');

// Initialize bot
const client = new Client({
  intents: [
    GatewayIntentBits.Guilds,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildMessages,
    GatewayIntentBits.MessageContent, // Required for message content
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildMembers, // Required for ban command
  ],
  partials: [Partials.Message, Partials.Channel, Partials.GuildMember],
});

// Initialize REST
const rest = new REST({ version: '9' }).setToken(YOUR_BOT_TOKEN);

// Create a collection for commands
client.commands = new Collection();

// Ban command
const banCommand = {
  name: 'ban',
  description: 'Bans a user from the server',
  options: [
    {
      name: 'user',
      description: 'User to ban',
      type: 'USER',
      required: true,
    },
    {
      name: 'reason',
      description: 'Reason for the ban',
      type: 'STRING',
      required: false,
    },
  ],
  async execute(interaction) {
    const user = interaction.options.getUser('user');
    const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason') || 'No reason provided';

    try {
      const member = await interaction.guild.members.fetch(user.id);
      await member.ban({ reason });
      await interaction.reply(`${user.tag} has been banned.`);
    } catch (error) {
      console.error(error);
      await interaction.reply('There was an error banning the user.');
    }
  },
};

// Add ban command to commands collection
client.commands.set(banCommand.name, banCommand);

// Register slash commands
async function registerCommands() {
  try {
    console.log('Started refreshing application (/) commands.');
    await rest.put(Routes.applicationCommands(YOUR_CLIENT_ID), {
      body: client.commands.map((command) => command.toJSON()),
    });
    console.log('Successfully reloaded application (/) commands.');
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
  }
}

// Bot event listeners
client.on('ready', () => {
  console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);
  registerCommands();
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  const command = client.commands.get(interaction.commandName);
  if (!command) return;

  try {
    await command.execute(interaction);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
    await interaction.reply('There was an error executing the command.');
  }
});

// Replace YOUR_BOT_TOKEN and YOUR_CLIENT_ID with your bot token and client id
client.login(YOUR_BOT_TOKEN);
```

Replace `YOUR_BOT_TOKEN` and `YOUR_CLIENT_ID` with your bot token and client ID, respectively. You can find these values in the Discord Developer Portal.

To run your bot, execute `node bot.js` in your console. Ensure that the bot has the necessary permissions to execute the ban command in your Discord server.

Here's a simple C++ function that converts some basic markdown formatting to HTML. This function handles bold, italic, and headings. Please note that this is a simplified version and doesn't cover all possible markdown features.

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    std::regex boldRegex("\\*\\*(.*?)\\*\\*");
    std::regex italicRegex("\\*(.*?)\\*");
    std::regex headingRegex("^(#{1,6})\\s+(.*)$", std::regex_constants::multiline);

    // Bold
    html = std::regex_replace(markdown, boldRegex, "<strong>$1</strong>");

    // Italic
    html = std::regex_replace(html, italicRegex, "<em>$1</em>");

    // Headings
    html = std::regex_replace(html, headingRegex, "<h$1>$2</h$1>");

    return html;
}
```

This function uses the `std::regex_replace` function to replace markdown syntax with corresponding HTML tags. The `boldRegex` finds double asterisks (`**`) surrounded by any characters (`.*?`) and replaces them with `<strong>` and `</strong>` tags. The `italicRegex` does the same for single asterisks (`*`) and the `<em>` and `</em>` tags. The `headingRegex` finds lines that start with one to six hash symbols (`#`), followed by a space and any characters, and replaces them with the appropriate heading level (`<h1>` to `<h6>`).

Creating a smooth, image-based Snake game in C from scratch is quite a complex task, but I can certainly guide you through the process. We'll use the Allegro library for handling graphics and images. Here's a basic outline:

1. Install Allegro: Allegro is a cross-platform library primarily for game development. You can download it from https://www.allegro.cc/ or use a package manager in your OS.

2. Setup: Include necessary libraries and define constants.

```c
#include <allegro.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

#define WIDTH 800
#define HEIGHT 600
#define SPEED 5
#define BLOCK_SIZE 10
```

3. Define structures for Snake and Game.

```c
typedef struct {
    int x, y;
} Point;

typedef struct {
    Point points[100];
    int size;
    int direction;
} Snake;

typedef struct {
    Snake snake;
    Point food;
} Game;
```

4. Initialize Allegro, display, images, etc.

```c
void init() {
    allegro_init();
    install_keyboard();
    set_color_depth(32);
    set_gfx_mode(GFX_AUTODETECT_WINDOWED, WIDTH, HEIGHT, 0, 0);
    srand(time(NULL));
}
```

5. Load images for snake, food, and background.

```c
BITMAP* snake_img = load_bitmap("snake.bmp", NULL);
BITMAP* food_img = load_bitmap("food.bmp", NULL);
BITMAP* background_img = load_bitmap("background.bmp", NULL);
```

6. Initialize game objects.

```c
void initGame(Game* game) {
    game->snake.size = 3;
    game->snake.direction = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < game->snake.size; i++) {
        game->snake.points[i].x = 50 - i * BLOCK_SIZE;
        game->snake.points[i].y = 50;
    }
    game->food.x = rand() % (WIDTH / BLOCK_SIZE) * BLOCK_SIZE;
    game->food.y = rand() % (HEIGHT / BLOCK_SIZE) * BLOCK_SIZE;
}
```

7. Update the game state.

```c
void update(Game* game) {
    for (int i = game->snake.size - 1; i > 0; i--) {
        game->snake.points[i] = game->snake.points[i - 1];
    }

    switch (game->snake.direction) {
        case 0: game->snake.points[0].y -= BLOCK_SIZE; break;
        case 1: game->snake.points[0].x += BLOCK_SIZE; break;
        case 2: game->snake.points[0].y += BLOCK_SIZE; break;
        case 3: game->snake.points[0].x -= BLOCK_SIZE; break;
    }

    if (game->snake.points[0].x == game->food.x && game->snake.points[0].y == game->food.y) {
        game->snake.size++;
        game->food.x = rand() % (WIDTH / BLOCK_SIZE) * BLOCK_SIZE;
        game->food.y = rand() % (HEIGHT / BLOCK_SIZE) * BLOCK_SIZE;
    }
}
```

8. Draw everything on the screen.

```c
void draw(Game* game) {
    blit(background_img, screen, 0, 0, 0, 0, WIDTH, HEIGHT);
    for (int i = 0; i < game->snake.size; i++) {
        draw_sprite(screen, snake_img, game->snake.points[i].x, game->snake.points[i].y);
    }
    draw_sprite(screen, food_img, game->food.x, game->food.y);
}
```

9. Main game loop.

```c
void gameLoop(Game* game) {
    while (!key[KEY_ESC]) {
        if (key[KEY_UP] && game->snake.direction != 2) game->snake.direction = 0;
        if (key[KEY_RIGHT] && game->snake.direction != 3) game->snake.direction = 1;
        if (key[KEY_DOWN] && game->snake.direction != 0) game->snake.direction = 2;
        if (key[KEY_LEFT] && game->snake.direction != 1) game->snake.direction = 3;

        update(game);
        draw(game);
        rest(SPEED);
    }
}
```

10. Main function.

```c
int main() {
    Game game;
    init();
    initGame(&game);
    gameLoop(&game);
    return 0;
}
```

