```

This function works by first checking if the number is less than or equal to 1, in which case it is not prime. Then it checks if the number is less than or equal to 3, in which case it is prime. After that, it checks if the number is divisible by 2 or 3. If it is, then it is not prime.

Finally, it checks the remaining numbers by starting at 5 and incrementing by 6 each time (since all primes are of the form 6k ± 1). If the number is divisible by any of these, then it is not prime. If the function has not returned False by the end of these checks, then the number is prime.

This function is relatively efficient, as it only checks divisibility up to the square root of the number and skips even numbers (except for 2) and numbers divisible by 3.

